{
  "card_id": "external_range_liquidity",
  "type": "merged_concept",
  "canonical_term": "External Range Liquidity",
  "aliases": [
    "erl",
    "ERL",
    "External Liquidity",
    "Old Highs",
    "old highs",
    "Old Lows",
    "old lows",
    "旧低点",
    "旧高点"
  ],
  "school": "ICT",
  "definition": "External Range Liquidity refers to swing highs and swing lows outside a defined price range, where resting stop orders accumulate (buy-side at highs, sell-side at lows). Price cycles between external and internal range liquidity (fair value gaps) in a fractal pattern across timeframes, moving from internal to external and back.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Mark swing highs and swing lows (including session/range extremes such as Asia, London, New York, previous day/week high/low) as external range liquidity; swing highs represent buy-side liquidity (resting buy stops), swing lows represent sell-side liquidity (resting sell stops).",
    "Confirm external liquidity is taken when price trades beyond the swing high or swing low of the defined range.",
    "A stop raid (sweep) in the opposite direction often precedes a move to external liquidity.",
    "If price sweeps an external level but fails to displace or break out, treat it as a liquidity grab returning into the range (especially in Seek and Destroy conditions where both sides may be swept without follow-through).",
    "After price interacts with internal range liquidity (e.g., a fair value gap) and respects it, the next target is the opposing external range liquidity (old high or old low).",
    "After price takes out external range liquidity, expect price to seek internal range liquidity (the nearest fair value gap) before continuing.",
    "External range liquidity levels are the most recent swing highs/lows beyond the current consolidation.",
    "Apply these rules on any timeframe (fractal: weekly, daily, hourly, 5-minute, 1-minute).",
    "Distinguish external range liquidity from Relatively Equal Highs/Lows: external liquidity is a single prominent swing point, not multiple clustered at similar levels.",
    "Determine if external liquidity has been swept: price pierces the high/low but closes back inside the range, indicating a liquidity sweep; if price closes outside, it is not a sweep reversal."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "External range liquidity provides directional bias and profit targets. After price respects internal liquidity (fair value gaps), continuation to the opposing external liquidity is expected, framing buy/sell models. Higher timeframes set weekly/daily bias; lower timeframes provide entry targets. Stops are placed beyond swept external levels, and runners can be held to higher-timeframe external targets. In non-displacement sweeps (e.g., Seek and Destroy conditions), traders fade the sweep back into the range targeting equilibrium or the opposite side. External liquidity can be used as take-profit targets and reversal points (short after sweeping high, long after sweeping low), with entries via fair value gaps, inversion fair value gaps, or order blocks.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Expecting a clean retracement to internal liquidity before every move to external — price may continue without retracing.",
    "Attempting to project the next leg before a fair value gap (internal liquidity) has actually formed.",
    "Treating a sweep of external liquidity as a breakout and trading in the direction of the sweep, when price fails to displace and reverts back into the range.",
    "Trying to play from inside the range outward during Seek and Destroy conditions instead of fading external liquidity back into equilibrium.",
    "Misidentifying a short-term swing as external range liquidity when it is actually internal, leading to premature target selection.",
    "Confusing Relatively Equal Highs/Lows with external range liquidity — external liquidity is a single prominent swing point, not multiple clustered levels.",
    "Using old swept swing highs/lows as valid external liquidity targets without updating to the most recent level.",
    "Expecting price to move to external liquidity before internal liquidity has been filled, ignoring the alternating sequence.",
    "Assuming a sweep is complete when price only touches the level but does not close back inside the range.",
    "Ignoring multiple timeframe external liquidity levels (weekly, daily, session), leading to incomplete target setting.",
    "Neglecting internal liquidity as a subsequent target after external liquidity is swept."
  ],
